We are from Japan,
some are from Japan.

00:39:12.962 --> 00:39:15.420
BRADLEY HOROWITZ: Anyone--
well, they're watching on video.

00:39:18.160 --> 00:39:21.440
SPEAKER: Oh, that's all?

00:39:21.440 --> 00:39:21.990
Thank you.

00:39:21.990 --> 00:39:23.090
RON KELLUM: OK, great.

00:39:23.090 --> 00:39:26.460
BRADLEY HOROWITZ: Do you have
names you want to share or not?

00:39:26.460 --> 00:39:27.440
SPEAKER: Yeah.

00:39:27.440 --> 00:39:28.850
My name is [NON-ENGLISH].

00:39:33.142 --> 00:39:34.100
BRADLEY HOROWITZ: Cool.

00:39:34.100 --> 00:39:34.930
Thank you.

00:39:34.930 --> 00:39:36.100
SPEAKER: Thank you.

00:39:36.100 --> 00:39:37.987
Nice to meet you.

00:39:37.987 --> 00:39:40.070
BRADLEY HOROWITZ: OK, let's
get to some questions.

00:39:40.070 --> 00:39:41.413
Green mic first.

00:39:41.413 --> 00:39:43.580
AUDIENCE: One topic of
conversation always at Google

00:39:43.580 --> 00:39:44.240
is trust--

00:39:44.240 --> 00:39:46.220
trust with our users,
trust with our peers,

00:39:46.220 --> 00:39:48.200
trust with our executive.

00:39:48.200 --> 00:39:50.240
Unless I miss my
guess, trust is sort of

00:39:50.240 --> 00:39:52.970
fundamental to the Circus world.

00:39:52.970 --> 00:39:56.600
Are there things that
you do within the family

00:39:56.600 --> 00:39:59.300
to help you build trust,
either at the head office

00:39:59.300 --> 00:40:00.800
or on the road,
things like that?

00:40:00.800 --> 00:40:07.480
Like, are there tricks that
you use or things that you do?

00:40:07.480 --> 00:40:09.700
BERNARD PETIOT: Maybe I
can talk with that process

00:40:09.700 --> 00:40:13.760
that we use when we're
developing an act.

00:40:13.760 --> 00:40:15.010
I'll take it as an example.

00:40:15.010 --> 00:40:17.177
You know the teeter board,
you know where the people

00:40:17.177 --> 00:40:21.250
are bouncing from both sides.

00:40:21.250 --> 00:40:23.740
In Montreal, I am
in charge of what

00:40:23.740 --> 00:40:26.390
we call the training before
they actually go on the show.

00:40:26.390 --> 00:40:30.620
So we are inviting people coming
from the trampoline world.

00:40:30.620 --> 00:40:33.640
And we could have
maybe people coming

00:40:33.640 --> 00:40:37.300
from France, from the US,
from Russia and et cetera,

00:40:37.300 --> 00:40:40.930
and they will meet
together right there.

00:40:40.930 --> 00:40:44.140
And then they have
to work together.

00:40:44.140 --> 00:40:47.980
And teeter board is
a very dangerous act.

00:40:47.980 --> 00:40:52.930
So what we do in order to
make sure that actually we

00:40:52.930 --> 00:40:58.900
create that trust is we go step
by step in terms of processes,

00:40:58.900 --> 00:41:03.120
having them to go through
all of the basics,

00:41:03.120 --> 00:41:05.120
all of the language.

00:41:05.120 --> 00:41:07.330
We also provide--

00:41:07.330 --> 00:41:10.630
I may have two or
three translator

00:41:10.630 --> 00:41:14.890
there to provide the appropriate
communication between all

00:41:14.890 --> 00:41:15.850
of them.

00:41:15.850 --> 00:41:18.640
I will have an artistic
coach, an acrobatic coach

00:41:18.640 --> 00:41:23.080
at the same time surrounding the
entire environment to make sure

00:41:23.080 --> 00:41:27.370
that they develop their own
dialogue and communication

00:41:27.370 --> 00:41:30.825
and they understand each other
in terms of who should do what

00:41:30.825 --> 00:41:33.940
and when and what kind of
reaction they should have.

00:41:33.940 --> 00:41:37.570
And they will go through weeks
of training and developing

00:41:37.570 --> 00:41:38.200
that.

00:41:38.200 --> 00:41:41.080
And then step by step,
OK, then the coach

00:41:41.080 --> 00:41:43.360
will step back, step
back, and then transfer

00:41:43.360 --> 00:41:45.580
that responsibility
of the group to manage

00:41:45.580 --> 00:41:48.300
the performance, to
dialogue between themselves,

00:41:48.300 --> 00:41:49.720
to brief and debrief.

00:41:49.720 --> 00:41:53.170
And that's what
Ron was saying is

00:41:53.170 --> 00:41:56.140
we develop, also, that
debriefing culture

00:41:56.140 --> 00:41:57.710
as part of the process.

00:41:57.710 --> 00:41:59.510
So then when the
performance is done,

00:41:59.510 --> 00:42:02.590
then they will revise it, look
at the video and the replay,

00:42:02.590 --> 00:42:06.310
and then talk about
it and self evaluate.

00:42:06.310 --> 00:42:07.780
RON KELLUM: Trust is number one.

00:42:07.780 --> 00:42:09.610
I mean, it's
unbelievable how critical

00:42:09.610 --> 00:42:11.470
these checks and balances are.

00:42:11.470 --> 00:42:13.120
And we take them daily.

00:42:13.120 --> 00:42:16.440
For example, when we have to
put a new artist into the show,

00:42:16.440 --> 00:42:20.670
they will never come to
us and go right on stage.

00:42:20.670 --> 00:42:24.605
We have to do a full show
validation in the reality

00:42:24.605 --> 00:42:26.230
that they're going
to be performing in.

00:42:26.230 --> 00:42:29.315
Just a change of the lights
can change their world.

00:42:29.315 --> 00:42:30.940
And if they don't
understand that, they

00:42:30.940 --> 00:42:33.640
haven't had a chance
to prepare, it

00:42:33.640 --> 00:42:35.720
can become a challenge for them.

00:42:35.720 --> 00:42:36.590
So absolutely.

00:42:36.590 --> 00:42:39.480
And that's how we build that
into our systems and balance.

00:42:39.480 --> 00:42:40.050
Yeah.

00:42:40.050 --> 00:42:41.590
AUDIENCE: [NON-ENGLISH].

00:42:41.590 --> 00:42:43.923
BRADLEY HOROWITZ: This is a
slightly different question,

00:42:43.923 --> 00:42:47.920
but these artists who are at
the top of their game and rock

00:42:47.920 --> 00:42:49.960
stars in their
respective disciplines,

00:42:49.960 --> 00:42:53.200
sometimes rock stars can
develop rock star attitudes

00:42:53.200 --> 00:42:56.302
and be a little bit
diva-like or Prima Donna.

00:42:56.302 --> 00:43:01.720
[LAUGHTER]

00:43:01.720 --> 00:43:04.210
Have you ever-- like, do you
have to work on that, too?

00:43:04.210 --> 00:43:07.720
Like, have you asked
people to leave that can't

00:43:07.720 --> 00:43:09.820
get with the family--

00:43:09.820 --> 00:43:13.600
we all have strange
uncles, but is

00:43:13.600 --> 00:43:17.560
that part of this, sort of
making sure that people really

00:43:17.560 --> 00:43:20.110
do have the right attitude,
as well as the right talent?

00:43:20.110 --> 00:43:22.000
RON KELLUM: That is a
key part of the job,

00:43:22.000 --> 00:43:25.360
as well, is really maintaining
the family environment,

00:43:25.360 --> 00:43:26.680
that there is no--

00:43:26.680 --> 00:43:28.180
if you think about
Cirque de Soleil,

00:43:28.180 --> 00:43:30.855
there is no name other than Guy.

00:43:30.855 --> 00:43:31.730
You know what I mean?

00:43:31.730 --> 00:43:34.780
You don't hear of the
artist performing in--

00:43:34.780 --> 00:43:35.970
Cirque is the stars.

00:43:35.970 --> 00:43:37.540
Cirque is the brand.

00:43:37.540 --> 00:43:40.030
We want the artists to
understand that we all

00:43:40.030 --> 00:43:41.870
bring a contribution to it.

00:43:41.870 --> 00:43:45.460
And there are times that
some artists can't fit inside

00:43:45.460 --> 00:43:46.560
of this bubble.

00:43:46.560 --> 00:43:48.277
And we respect that
because we always

00:43:48.277 --> 00:43:50.110
encourage people to
find where your light is

00:43:50.110 --> 00:43:51.700
going to shine the brightest.

00:43:51.700 --> 00:43:53.590
That's the most important thing.

00:43:53.590 --> 00:43:55.870
If it doesn't feel
like it's bright here,

00:43:55.870 --> 00:43:58.300
we will support you in finding
that place that's right.

00:43:58.300 --> 00:44:00.236
BRADLEY HOROWITZ: That is a
great way to give feedback.

00:44:00.236 --> 00:44:00.736
Thank you.

00:44:00.736 --> 00:44:01.736
We're going to use that.

00:44:01.736 --> 00:44:03.778
BERNARD PETIOT: It's a
very interesting question,

00:44:03.778 --> 00:44:05.830
because if-- and I look
at the casting at large,

00:44:05.830 --> 00:44:07.372
we've got circus
professionals, we've

00:44:07.372 --> 00:44:11.190
got people coming from the arts,
singing, dancers, and musicians

00:44:11.190 --> 00:44:11.690
and so on.

00:44:11.690 --> 00:44:15.190
But we also have more than
30% coming from sport.

00:44:15.190 --> 00:44:18.112
And from sport you
want to be the best.

00:44:18.112 --> 00:44:19.320
You want to be on the podium.

00:44:19.320 --> 00:44:22.240
So when you leave
that culture and you

00:44:22.240 --> 00:44:25.000
come to our
environment, then you're

00:44:25.000 --> 00:44:26.620
becoming part of that family.

00:44:26.620 --> 00:44:30.640
So you're engaged to
develop that ability

00:44:30.640 --> 00:44:33.970
to actually sort of
personally disappear and be

00:44:33.970 --> 00:44:35.710
a contributor to the show.

00:44:35.710 --> 00:44:38.980
And we ensure that
this process is also

00:44:38.980 --> 00:44:40.973
part of what we do in
Montreal to make sure

00:44:40.973 --> 00:44:42.890
that these people that
we are coming with that

00:44:42.890 --> 00:44:46.240
see gold medal at
Worlds or Olympics,

00:44:46.240 --> 00:44:49.090
they will put that here.

00:44:49.090 --> 00:44:52.390
And now they will adopt the
culture of Cirque du Soleil.

00:44:52.390 --> 00:44:53.525
BRADLEY HOROWITZ: Amazing.

00:44:53.525 --> 00:44:55.660
OK, yellow mic.

00:44:55.660 --> 00:44:58.672
AUDIENCE: Hi, thank you for
coming and talking to us.

00:44:58.672 --> 00:45:00.130
I was wondering,
how much time does

00:45:00.130 --> 00:45:02.130
it take from the time
you conceptualize

00:45:02.130 --> 00:45:04.470
a show to the time it opens?

00:45:04.470 --> 00:45:07.320
And within that time
period, how much time

00:45:07.320 --> 00:45:12.810
is spent in choreography and
training and things like that?

00:45:12.810 --> 00:45:17.340
BERNARD PETIOT: It could take
from the initial team and then

00:45:17.340 --> 00:45:20.100
the selection of
the stage director

00:45:20.100 --> 00:45:23.370
and a couple of other creators,
the director of creation

00:45:23.370 --> 00:45:27.450
and so on, from
two to three years.

00:45:27.450 --> 00:45:30.000
Then that is
basically developing

00:45:30.000 --> 00:45:35.070
from the idea the whole concept,
and through that journey,

00:45:35.070 --> 00:45:38.640
is also identifying, OK,
the different profiles

00:45:38.640 --> 00:45:41.352
of artists that will be needed.

00:45:41.352 --> 00:45:43.560
And then, so that we can
proceed through the casting,

00:45:43.560 --> 00:45:45.600
because casting
takes a long time.

00:45:45.600 --> 00:45:50.970
And sometimes also it's also
being influenced by immigration

00:45:50.970 --> 00:45:53.338
and all sorts of obstacles.

00:45:53.338 --> 00:45:55.380
And then after that, we
have the training period.

00:45:55.380 --> 00:45:57.297
The training period,
let's see, as an example,

00:45:57.297 --> 00:46:00.270
the big top that we will
be producing in April,

00:46:00.270 --> 00:46:04.200
then we started the training
period last September,

00:46:04.200 --> 00:46:06.030
last year in 2018.

00:46:06.030 --> 00:46:11.550
And then from fall to December,
then we only did the training.

00:46:11.550 --> 00:46:14.030
And at the same time,
then the costume

00:46:14.030 --> 00:46:16.110
were designed,
developed, and so on,

00:46:16.110 --> 00:46:18.390
and all sorts of other
technical aspects

00:46:18.390 --> 00:46:20.650
were developed, and
equipment, and so on.

00:46:20.650 --> 00:46:23.460
And then January, then
you start the rehearsal.

00:46:23.460 --> 00:46:26.730
And the rehearsal
continues up to the moment

00:46:26.730 --> 00:46:31.200
that we transfer in April,
in March, under the big top.

00:46:31.200 --> 00:46:33.900
And that whole rehearsal
is being done in Montreal,

00:46:33.900 --> 00:46:35.333
in a big, big studio.

00:46:35.333 --> 00:46:36.750
That's so we could
do that inside,

00:46:36.750 --> 00:46:38.590
because it's cold in Montreal.

00:46:38.590 --> 00:46:41.080
And then after that,
we transfer in April.

00:46:41.080 --> 00:46:42.750
And then we will be
opening, let's see,

00:46:42.750 --> 00:46:48.125
this new show
"Allegria" by mid-April.

00:46:48.125 --> 00:46:49.500
BRADLEY HOROWITZ:
Great question.

00:46:49.500 --> 00:46:51.540
Yes, green mic.

00:46:51.540 --> 00:46:53.580
AUDIENCE: I watched
the show last Saturday.

00:46:53.580 --> 00:46:54.980
It was amazing.

00:46:54.980 --> 00:46:56.380
So I have a question.

00:46:56.380 --> 00:46:59.010
So I remember in the
show there is an artist,

00:46:59.010 --> 00:47:01.500
I think her name is Danila Kim.

00:47:01.500 --> 00:47:06.630
She was dancing along on
the stage with her hair tied

00:47:06.630 --> 00:47:08.400
and the hand on top.

00:47:08.400 --> 00:47:11.630
That part was very different
from the rest of show.

00:47:11.630 --> 00:47:14.580
So from the perspective
of storytelling,

00:47:14.580 --> 00:47:17.400
could you help me understand
how this part fits

00:47:17.400 --> 00:47:19.410
the rest of the story?

00:47:19.410 --> 00:47:21.450
RON KELLUM: I don't know
if I got the question.

00:47:21.450 --> 00:47:23.033
BRADLEY HOROWITZ:
From the perspective

00:47:23.033 --> 00:47:24.900
of sort storytelling,
how does that element

00:47:24.900 --> 00:47:26.340
fit in with the
rest of the show?

00:47:26.340 --> 00:47:28.300
Because she found it
to be very different.

00:47:28.300 --> 00:47:30.300
RON KELLUM: I love that
you asked that question.

00:47:30.300 --> 00:47:33.240
The idea, the
conceptor is always

00:47:33.240 --> 00:47:36.660
thinking, for us as
individuals, we put on a mask

00:47:36.660 --> 00:47:40.560
or we put on our armor every day
when we walk out of the door.

00:47:40.560 --> 00:47:43.230
And the goal is,
take off the armor.

00:47:43.230 --> 00:47:44.700
Take off your mask.

00:47:44.700 --> 00:47:46.673
And then fly higher.

00:47:46.673 --> 00:47:48.840
So when we get to the part
of the show with the hair

00:47:48.840 --> 00:47:51.690
suspension, it's all
about fly as high

00:47:51.690 --> 00:47:55.830
as you can and let it sort feel
like you're in outer space,

00:47:55.830 --> 00:47:57.570
where there is no gravity.

00:47:57.570 --> 00:47:59.797
You know, that's the
idea of hair suspension.

00:47:59.797 --> 00:48:00.630
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:48:00.630 --> 00:48:01.500
RON KELLUM: Did that help?

00:48:01.500 --> 00:48:02.156
AUDIENCE: Yes.

00:48:02.156 --> 00:48:04.590
BRADLEY HOROWITZ: Beautiful.

00:48:04.590 --> 00:48:05.220
Yes.

00:48:05.220 --> 00:48:06.928
AUDIENCE: Thank you
very much for coming.

00:48:06.928 --> 00:48:09.900
I can imagine with the degree
that safety is important

00:48:09.900 --> 00:48:12.900
and the degree that all of this
is transpiling in front of us

00:48:12.900 --> 00:48:15.720
live that it can be
very difficult to make

00:48:15.720 --> 00:48:16.988
the go or no go call.

00:48:16.988 --> 00:48:18.780
And that's something
that the general stage

00:48:18.780 --> 00:48:21.540
manager, the performer, is
that ever a difficult thing

00:48:21.540 --> 00:48:24.420
with this feeling of
the show must go on

00:48:24.420 --> 00:48:26.520
to be able to negotiate
what is possible

00:48:26.520 --> 00:48:30.150
and what's impossible as things
go, as people miss tricks,

00:48:30.150 --> 00:48:32.950
as people say, I can
do it the next time?

00:48:32.950 --> 00:48:34.080
RON KELLUM: Great question.

00:48:34.080 --> 00:48:35.430
100%.

00:48:35.430 --> 00:48:37.620
There is that moment
where we all have

00:48:37.620 --> 00:48:38.970
to make a collective decision.

00:48:38.970 --> 00:48:42.630
And I always say more
heads together are better,

00:48:42.630 --> 00:48:45.930
because when we get to those
moments where it can be

00:48:45.930 --> 00:48:47.250
we've pushed too hard.

00:48:47.250 --> 00:48:49.140
Fatigue could be setting in.

00:48:49.140 --> 00:48:52.920
Or the environment that we're
in just not sustainable, we do

00:48:52.920 --> 00:48:54.090
have to make that decision.

00:48:54.090 --> 00:48:55.835
The show does not go on.

00:48:55.835 --> 00:48:57.210
It's something
that we don't like

00:48:57.210 --> 00:48:59.940
to do because we respect
that our audiences come

00:48:59.940 --> 00:49:03.240
from all over to see a
Cirque de Soleil show.

00:49:03.240 --> 00:49:06.300
We respect that many times,
when someone comes to our show,

00:49:06.300 --> 00:49:09.780
it's for a 50 year wedding
anniversary, a birthday

00:49:09.780 --> 00:49:10.440
celebration.

00:49:10.440 --> 00:49:12.240
They're very
special moments what

00:49:12.240 --> 00:49:14.190
gets people under the big top.

00:49:14.190 --> 00:49:15.820
So we want to deliver.

00:49:15.820 --> 00:49:19.420
But at the end of the day,
safety, safety, safety.

00:49:19.420 --> 00:49:21.510
And we take that into
consideration every day.

00:49:21.510 --> 00:49:23.260
BERNARD PETIOT: And
the phase of creation,

00:49:23.260 --> 00:49:26.400
it's interesting, also, of the
safety management, especially

00:49:26.400 --> 00:49:27.960
when we create an act.

00:49:27.960 --> 00:49:29.480
We will develop the equipment.

00:49:29.480 --> 00:49:32.190
The equipment will be
tested, engineered,

00:49:32.190 --> 00:49:34.140
and then we'll also
develop the act

00:49:34.140 --> 00:49:39.180
by selecting what
is sub-maximal.

00:49:39.180 --> 00:49:40.390
We're not in a competition.

00:49:40.390 --> 00:49:45.360
So we're not trying to
do the one best one time.

00:49:45.360 --> 00:49:47.550
We're making sure
that the content

00:49:47.550 --> 00:49:50.130
is being selected so that
it's within the resource

00:49:50.130 --> 00:49:51.610
of that individual.

00:49:51.610 --> 00:49:55.110
And then we will also
test these over time

00:49:55.110 --> 00:49:58.080
to ensure that when it's
integrated in the act, then

00:49:58.080 --> 00:50:00.520
it will be sustained.

00:50:00.520 --> 00:50:02.620
So in fact, I
mean, your question

00:50:02.620 --> 00:50:03.790
is very, very interesting.

00:50:03.790 --> 00:50:07.270
And it's a preoccupation
of mine right

00:50:07.270 --> 00:50:08.950
from the onset of creation.

00:50:08.950 --> 00:50:11.470
How far should we push?

00:50:11.470 --> 00:50:12.970
Obviously, we're doing circus.

00:50:12.970 --> 00:50:16.280
So there is a risk there.

00:50:16.280 --> 00:50:19.120
And then we're creating
every processes

00:50:19.120 --> 00:50:22.210
that is possible to ensure that
not only we select people that

00:50:22.210 --> 00:50:24.670
are really good from
the onset, but also we

00:50:24.670 --> 00:50:27.550
make all the progression
and the steps

00:50:27.550 --> 00:50:30.220
to verify and validate
these performances

00:50:30.220 --> 00:50:32.860
under various circumstances
up to the show

00:50:32.860 --> 00:50:36.670
condition with lighting
and music, and so on.

00:50:36.670 --> 00:50:38.700
AUDIENCE: Thank you very much.

